Abstract = {In recent years there has been a dramatic rise in the number of comparative studies of groups within culturally plural nation states. There are 2 models that may serve as frameworks for guiding such research—the unicultural and the cross-cultural. An argument is advanced that research in plural societies requires a new model, one that draws primarily upon the cross-cultural model, reflecting an ideology of cultural pluralism, so that the independence and uniqueness of each group in the comparison may be respected. A transethnic model is proposed for conducting comparative studies of ethunits in polyethnic societies. Guidelines for assessing issues of comparability, group independence, and the number of groups in the comparison and their cultural characteristics are discussed. (29 ref) (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2012 APA, all rights reserved)},
