@article{1983-02735-00119810101,
Abstract = {Examines the polyethnic behavior of termites in 5 experiments. The cephalic gland defensive secretion of the nasute soldiers produced short-term recruitment of only soldiers to loci where it was present. Workers reacted to the secretion by remaining in or retreating to the nest. The sternal gland secretion of workers and soldiers acted in long-term recruitment of soldiers when presented as a point source, a trail, or a trail with a food source at its end. This secretion caused more exiting soldiers than the cephalic gland secretion and was more effective in this regard as a trail than as a point source. The greater numbers exiting in the trail situation may be related to the greater amount of pheromone area present and the halting of soldiers at the pheromone odor boundary. The greatest number of soldiers exited when the trail was coupled with a food source at its end, and in this situation workers exited for the 1st time in significant numbers. Additional information about the food source is postulated to be communicated by tactile means (jittering), and it is suggested that this lowers the threshold for the trail-following responses in Ss such that worker exiting is initiated. (24 ref) (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2013 APA, all rights reserved)},
